<subSubSection id="C33CC7BBFFEA7D20899FF95A0730E13D" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="586" pageId="4" pageNumber="585" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEA7D21899FF95A0655E100" blockId="4.[151,1436,1708,1914]" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEA7D21899FF95A040BE0BF" bold="true" box="[151,266,1708,1733]" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Easily recognized by the distinctive male and female genitalia. In the male genitalia, saccus clearly in two fused parts, a dorsal and a ventral ones. Fultura superior present. In the female genitalia, the lamella antevaginalis is compound mainly by two tapered processes latero-anterior that extends and fuses posteriorly to a mesal process, forming a depression between both structures. Such structures are unique among all Neotropical genera. In addition, the new genus is diagnosed by the combination of the following characters in head micromorphology, wing venation, wing pattern, and abdomen:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEA7D21899FF85C06BAE1B8" blockId="4.[151,1038,1961,2022]" box="[151,955,1961,1986]" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">• male labial palpus with first and second palpomeres partially fused,</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEA7D20899FF838077CE682" blockId="4.[151,1038,1961,2022]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1001,151,248]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="586" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">
• in the female the second palpomere twice the length of the first palpomere, • 'hepialine' venation (Rs2+Rs3 not stalked with Rs4) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7E9C1FFEB7D208A12FF6106DCE6CA" author="Dumbleton, L. J." box="[794,989,151,176]" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Science, 9" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" pagination="920 - 981" part="4" refString="Dumbleton, L. J. (1966) Genitalia, classification and zoogeography of the New Zealand Hepialidae (Lepidoptera). New Zealand Journal of Science, 9 (4), 920 - 981." title="Genitalia, classification and zoogeography of the New Zealand Hepialidae (Lepidoptera)" type="journal article" year="1966">Dumbleton 1966</bibRefCitation>
), • absence of distinct banding or patches on the forewing, • sternum VIII of the male membranous.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF59C4B8FFEB7D20899FFA4A05D8E055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/998528/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" targetBox="[160,1415,307,1447]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEB7D20899FFA4A05D8E055" blockId="5.[151,1436,1468,1583]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D20899FFA4A0451E3A8" bold="true" box="[151,336,1468,1491]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">FIGURES 16−21</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D208857FA4B0743E3A9" baseAuthorityName="Viette" baseAuthorityYear="1956" box="[351,578,1469,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Cibyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pluriargenteus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208857FA4B0743E3A9" box="[351,578,1469,1491]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Cibyra pluriargenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 16−17. Male abdomen (MZSP 30.629): 16, upper dorsal, lower ventral view; 17, tergum and sternum VII and VIII; 18, Male genitalia, ventral view (MZSP 30.629); 19, Female tergum and sternum VII and VIII (MZSP 30.626); 20−21, Female genitalia: 20, lateral view (MZSP 30.625); 21, posterior view (MZSP 30.626). Scale bar = 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEB7D2089CFF9A00730E13D" blockId="5.[151,1436,1622,2007]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">
The arched shape of the male genitalia resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D208BF6F9A006F2E015" authority="Viette, 1961" authorityName="Viette" authorityYear="1961" box="[766,1011,1622,1647]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Phialuse" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208BF6F9A00661E015" box="[766,864,1622,1647]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Phialuse</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7E9C1FFEB7D208A61F9A006F2E015" author="Viette, P." box="[873,1011,1622,1647]" journalOrPublisher="Opuscula Zoologica" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" pagination="1 - 7" part="55" refString="Viette, P. (1961) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Insektenfauna Boliviens XV. Lepidoptera II. Contribution a l'etude des Hepialidae. 34 eme note. Especes sud-americaines nouvelles ou peu connues du Museum de Munich. Opuscula Zoologica, 55, 1 - 7." title="Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Insektenfauna Boliviens XV. Lepidoptera II. Contribution a l'etude des Hepialidae. 34 eme note. Especes sud-americaines nouvelles ou peu connues du Museum de Munich" type="journal article" year="1961">Viette, 1961</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with respect to an extended structure attached to the ventral surface of the saccus, although no particular relationship can be inferred to present time, since other characters such as antennae and wing characteristics are very different. The membranous tergum VIII of the female suggests a close relation with 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D208B84F93407DBE0A1" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1856" box="[652,730,1730,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Cibyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208B84F93407DBE0A1" box="[652,730,1730,1755]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Cibyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D208A1BF9350132E0A1" authority="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" box="[787,1075,1730,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Aepytus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208A1BF935066DE0A0" box="[787,876,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Aepytus</emphasis>
Herrich-Schäffer
</taxonomicName>
, [1856], but the presence of the fultura superior (trulleum) in the male genitalia contradicts its phylogenetic position from these genera. The shape of sternum II and its anterior lateral bar are also similar to other cibyrine genera, to 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D208D4BF8FC006DE159" authority="Viette, 1951" authorityName="Viette" authorityYear="1951" box="[1091,1388,1802,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Hepialyxodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208D4BF8FC01DDE159" box="[1091,1244,1802,1827]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Hepialyxodes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7E9C1FFEB7D208DEBF8FC006DE159" author="Viette, P." box="[1251,1388,1802,1827]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin mensuel de la Societe Linneenne de Lyon" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" pagination="95 - 96" part="20" publicationUrl="https://doi.org/10.3406/linly.1951.7396" refString="Viette, P. (1951) Contribution a l'etude des Hepialides (Lepid.) (24 note). Bulletin mensuel de la Societe Linneenne de Lyon, 20 (4), 95 - 96. https: // doi. org / 10.3406 / linly. 1951.7396" title="Contribution a l'etude des Hepialides (Lepid.) (24 note)" type="journal article" year="1951">Viette, 1951</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFEB7D20899FF8D905F1E13C" box="[151,240,1839,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Aepytus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D20899FF8D905F1E13C" box="[151,240,1839,1862]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Aepytus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in particular (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB7E9C1FFEB7D208885F8D80724E13D" author="Grehan, J. R" box="[397,549,1838,1863]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Buffalo Society of Natural Sciences" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" pagination="1 - 30" part="42" refString="Grehan, J. R (2012) Morphological evidence for phylogenetic relationships within the Hepialidae (Lepidoptera: Exoporia). Bulletin of the Buffalo Society of Natural Sciences, 42, 1 - 30." title="Morphological evidence for phylogenetic relationships within the Hepialidae (Lepidoptera: Exoporia)" type="journal article" year="2012">Grehan 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33CC7BBFFEB7D2289CFF8A40659E328" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="588" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEB7D2089CFF8A4009DE110" blockId="5.[151,1436,1622,2007]" box="[199,1436,1874,1899]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D2089CFF8A40450E111" bold="true" box="[199,337,1874,1899]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D208857F8A40499E111" box="[351,408,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131D88B5FFEB7D2088AEF8A40727E111" box="[422,550,1874,1899]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 − 15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1375,1398]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,628,1354]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,628,1354]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 − 15. Limyra silvai sp. nov. 11, male holotype, dorsal view; 12, male holotype, ventral view; 13, male paratype, dorsal view (MZSP 14.403); 14, female paratype, dorsal view (MZSP 14.404); 15, female paratype, ventral view (MZSP 14.404). Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/998526/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Figs 11–13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131D88B5FFEB7D208B39F8A50750E111" box="[561,593,1875,1899]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 − 29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1386,1409]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,207,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1365]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 22 − 29. Limyra silvai sp. nov. 22. Male abdomen (holotype), upper dorsal, lower ventral view. 23 − 25. Male genitalia (holotype): 23, ventral view; 24, lateral view; 25, anterior view (internal), fultura superior (arrow). 26 − 27. Female abdomen (MZSP 14.404). 26, upper dorsal, lower ventral view; 27, tergum and sternum VII and VIII (tergum VIII membranous), sternum VIII (arrow). 28 − 29. Female genitalia (MZSP 14.404). 28, lateral view; 29, posterior view. Scale bar = 1 mm, except Figs 22 and 26 = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/998530/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">22</figureCitation>
). Medium sized moths with wingspan ranging wingspan from 
<quantity id="4CDE39D5FFEB7D208C00F8A50099E110" box="[1288,1432,1875,1899]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.85" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="586" unit="mm" value="38.5" valueMax="43.0" valueMin="34.0">34 to 43 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B999430FFEB7D2089CFF8800445E1AD" blockId="5.[151,1436,1622,2007]" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFEB7D2089CFF880040AE1F5" box="[199,267,1910,1935]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="586">Head.</emphasis>
Clypeus glabrous anteriorly and medially projected, and fairly well differentiated from the frons. Labial palpus stout, first and second palpomeres partially fused. Antenna bipectinate, sensilla trichodea and sensilla caetica present.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF59C4B8FFE87D23899FFA9C0711E381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/998530/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="587" targetBox="[152,1430,207,1365]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph id="8B999430FFE87D23899FFA9C0711E381" blockId="6.[151,1436,1386,1531]" pageId="6" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFE87D23899FFA9C0452E3FA" bold="true" box="[151,339,1386,1409]" pageId="6" pageNumber="587">FIGURES 22−29</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C26EFB3FFE87D23886DFA9A04F1E3FB" authority="Duarte, 2017" authorityName="Duarte" authorityYear="2017" box="[357,496,1387,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Limyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9524822FFE87D23886DFA9A04F1E3FB" box="[357,496,1387,1409]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="587">Limyra silvai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
